{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-03-25T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Manatees may seem slow and sleepy, but they have some surprising tricks under the surface. For starters, they are one of the few mammals that constantly replace their teeth. As old molars wear down from chewing gritty seagrass, new ones slowly roll forward like a conveyor belt—handy for an animal that eats for up to eight hours a day.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ManateeSpring_EN-US1203685327_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ManateeSpring_EN-US1203685327_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The secret life of manatees","Title":"Juvenile manatees in a freshwater spring, Crystal River, Florida","Copyright":"© Gregory Sweeney/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/28.90055,-82.59361/7?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=28.90055,-82.59361;S9;Crystal River, Florida&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260325_ManateeSpring\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Manatee+Appreciation+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260325_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260325_ManateeSpring"},"Ssd":"20260325","Name":"ManateeSpring","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"1203685327","FullDateString":"Mar 25, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"From above, East Lake Cherry Blossom Park in Wuhan, China, looks like a soft lilac cloud settled gently over the land. Thousands of cherry trees bloom at once, their pale petals forming a living canopy around a golden five-story pagoda at the park's heart. The pagoda rises in calm symmetry, its tiered rooflines glowing against the delicate pastels of spring.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WuhanCherryBlossom_EN-US5963967452_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WuhanCherryBlossom_EN-US5963967452_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":false},"Headline":"The shape of spring","Title":"Cherry blossoms at East Lake Cherry Blossom Park, Wuhan, China","Copyright":"© Zhang Qiao/VCG/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/30.595,114.2975/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=30.595,114.2975;S9;Wuhan, Hubei, China&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260324_WuhanCherryBlossom\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Wuhan+China&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260324_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260324_WuhanCherryBlossom"},"Ssd":"20260324","Name":"WuhanCherryBlossom","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5963967452","FullDateString":"Mar 24, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The strength of nature is nowhere more evident than in powerful storms. Scary? Yes. Fascinating? Even more so. Learning to understand and respect these forces helps humanity live more safely.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SonoranStorm_EN-US5792303901_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SonoranStorm_EN-US5792303901_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Guided by the weather","Title":"Lightning storm over saguaro cacti, Sonoran Desert, Arizona","Copyright":"© Jack Dykinga/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/32.248009,-112.91613/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=32.248009,-112.91613;S9;Sonoran Desert, Arizona&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260323_SonoranStorm\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Meteorological+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260323_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260323_SonoranStorm"},"Ssd":"20260323","Name":"SonoranStorm","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5792303901","FullDateString":"Mar 23, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today is World Water Day, declared by the UN in 1992 and first observed the following year. Humanity could no longer drift along—we had to safeguard the very currents that keep us alive. Few places capture that urgency like Lake Tanganyika, in the Great Rift Valley of eastern Africa. From space, it's a roughly 420‑mile ribbon linking Tanzania, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, and Zambia. At the shoreline, it's a 10-million-year-old rift basin, formed as the Earth's crust slowly pulled apart.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TanganyikaWater_EN-US5685685365_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TanganyikaWater_EN-US5685685365_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"When water draws the line","Title":"Lake Tanganyika, Africa","Copyright":"© BEST-BACKGROUNDS/NASA/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/-6.026425,29.475387/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=-6.026425,29.475387;S9;Lake Tanganyika, Africa&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260322_TanganyikaWater\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=world+water+day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260322_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260322_TanganyikaWater"},"Ssd":"20260322","Name":"TanganyikaWater","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5685685365","FullDateString":"Mar 22, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If Earth had a maintenance crew, forests would be spearheading it. They absorb carbon emissions, reduce soil erosion, safeguard biodiversity, influence rainfall, and help maintain clean water supplies. They still cover about 31% of the world's land area, yet their continued decline shows how vulnerable these natural systems have become. Vast stretches continue to be cleared for agriculture, infrastructure, and resource extraction, weakening ecosystems at an alarming rate.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LeteaForest_EN-US5404369914_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LeteaForest_EN-US5404369914_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Where roots run wild","Title":"Letea Forest, Danube Delta, Romania","Copyright":"© Wild Wonders of Europe/Widstrand/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The UN FAO estimates that about 24.7 million acres (10 million hectares) of forest are cut down each year.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260321_LeteaForest\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=International+Day+of+Forests&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260321_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260321_LeteaForest"},"Ssd":"20260321","Name":"LeteaForest","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5404369914","FullDateString":"Mar 21, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A white snowdrop is spring's quiet debut. No confetti, no countdown—just a delicate flower appearing as the spring equinox balances day and night. Snowdrops are among the first to bloom, often pushing through cold soil before winter fully packs up. Their drooping, bell-shaped flowers may look delicate, but they're built for early arrival. Special antifreeze proteins in their cells help them tolerate frost, making them well suited to unpredictable late-winter weather.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpringSnowdrops_EN-US5032204696_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpringSnowdrops_EN-US5032204696_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The quiet bloom of change","Title":"Snowdrops in spring","Copyright":"© klagyivik/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Collectors crazy about snowdrops are called galanthophiles.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260320_SpringSnowdrops\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=March+equinox&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260320_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260320_SpringSnowdrops"},"Ssd":"20260320","Name":"SpringSnowdrops","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"5032204696","FullDateString":"Mar 20, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"An egg-laying mammal. No teeth. Reptilian gait. Built-in body armor. If the short-beaked echidna sounds like a checklist of contradictions, that's because it is—and it owns it. Native to Australia, Tasmania, and parts of New Guinea, it's one of the few surviving monotremes, or mammals that lay eggs. Despite the headlines, it still qualifies as a mammal: it has fur, produces milk, and is warm-blooded. The twist? Milk is released through specialized skin patches rather than nipples, leaving the young to lap it up.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.EchidnaAustralia_EN-US7660451296_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.EchidnaAustralia_EN-US7660451296_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Spike your curiosity","Title":"Short-beaked echidna, Adelaide Hills, Australia","Copyright":"© Etienne Littlefair/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/-34.892811,138.836243/7?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=-34.892811,138.836243;S9;Adelaide Hills, South Australia&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260319_EchidnaAustralia\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Short-beaked+echidna&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260319_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260319_EchidnaAustralia"},"Ssd":"20260319","Name":"EchidnaAustralia","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"7660451296","FullDateString":"Mar 19, 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"April is National Frog Month, a time to appreciate one of nature's smallest yet most remarkable ambassadors. Frogs help balance insect populations and often serve as early indicators of environmental change, as their permeable skin readily responds to shifts in water and air quality. Their presence reveals much about the health of their habitats, making this month a fitting time to pause and recognize their vital role.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.JapaneseTreeFrog_EN-US6527297660_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.JapaneseTreeFrog_EN-US6527297660_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Hopping into April","Title":"Japanese tree frog in a pink morning glory","Copyright":"© Tetsuya Tanooka/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The oldest known 'proto-frog,' Triadobatrachus massinoti, lived about 250 million years ago during the Early Triassic period.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260401_JapaneseTreeFrog\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=National+Frog+Month&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260401_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260401_JapaneseTreeFrog"},"Ssd":"20260401","Name":"JapaneseTreeFrog","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6527297660","FullDateString":"Apr 1, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Paradise Cave makes a powerful first impression the moment visitors step inside. This vast limestone cavern lies deep within Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park in central Vietnam, a region marked by rugged mountains and countless hidden caves. Stretching over 19 miles, Paradise Cave is one of Asia's longest dry caves, and its scale is immediately apparent. High ceilings rise above the walkways, and layered patterns formed by mineral-rich water over millions of years line the walls.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.ParadiseCave_EN-US6470755729_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.ParadiseCave_EN-US6470755729_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Underground paradise","Title":"Paradise Cave, Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park, Vietnam","Copyright":"© Pakawat Thongcharoen/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/16.835573,106.743552/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=16.835573,106.743552;S9;Paradise Cave, Phong Nha-Ke Bang National Park, Vietnam&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260331_ParadiseCave\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Paradise+Cave+Vietnam&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260331_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260331_ParadiseCave"},"Ssd":"20260331","Name":"ParadiseCave","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6470755729","FullDateString":"Mar 31, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The demoiselle crane is a small yet striking migratory bird found across Central Asia, from their breeding grounds in the steppes of Kazakhstan, Mongolia, and northern China, to their wintering grounds in India, Nepal, and parts of Africa. With its elegant appearance—slender neck, long legs, and beautiful plumage—it is often considered one of the most graceful crane species. They are known for their intricate courtship dances, during which pairs engage in synchronized movements and calls, creating a beautiful spectacle.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.IndiaCranes_EN-US6414900321_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.IndiaCranes_EN-US6414900321_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Elegance in motion","Title":"Demoiselle cranes, India","Copyright":"© Axel Gomille/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"In North India, the demoiselle crane is called 'koonj' and is a symbol of grace and beauty in literature.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260330_IndiaCranes\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Demoiselle+cranes&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260330_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260330_IndiaCranes"},"Ssd":"20260330","Name":"IndiaCranes","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6414900321","FullDateString":"Mar 30, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Peggy's Cove is a small yet captivating village on the rugged coast of Nova Scotia that offers a glimpse of life by the sea. The village's most famous landmark is Peggy's Point Lighthouse—also known as Peggy's Cove Lighthouse—first established in 1868 and replaced by the current structure in 1915. For over a century, it has guided ships through the ever-changing Atlantic waters, serving as a timeless symbol of coastal life. The surrounding landscape, with its windswept beauty and crashing waves, feels almost untouched by time.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PeggysLighthouse_EN-US6365734559_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PeggysLighthouse_EN-US6365734559_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Serenity by the sea","Title":"Peggy's Point Lighthouse, Atlantic Coast, Nova Scotia, Canada","Copyright":"© Prashanth Bala/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/44.492264,-63.918158/6?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=44.492264,-63.918158;S9;Peggy's Point Lighthouse, Atlantic Coast, Nova Scotia, Canada&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260329_PeggysLighthouse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Peggys+Point+Lighthouse&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260329_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260329_PeggysLighthouse"},"Ssd":"20260329","Name":"PeggysLighthouse","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6365734559","FullDateString":"Mar 29, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The African buffalo, a powerful and imposing creature, roams the savannas and wetlands of Tanzania, particularly within the Ngorongoro Conservation Area (NCA). Known for their large, curved horns and massive size, they are one of Africa's 'Big Five' (buffalo, elephant, leopard, rhino, lion) and are widely respected for their strength and resilience. The NCA, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, offers a dramatic and ecologically rich setting for observing these formidable herbivores.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CapeBuffalo_EN-US6304011521_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CapeBuffalo_EN-US6304011521_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The untamed spirit","Title":"African buffalo, Ngorongoro Crater, Tanzania","Copyright":"© jesuss8/500px/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/-3.064646,35.381698/5?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=-3.064646,35.381698;S9;Ngorongoro Crater, Tanzania&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260328_CapeBuffalo\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=African+buffalo&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260328_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260328_CapeBuffalo"},"Ssd":"20260328","Name":"CapeBuffalo","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6304011521","FullDateString":"Mar 28, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"At first glance, there's no doubt that the interior of Radio City Music Hall pulls you in and cranks up the excitement. It feels like stepping straight into the sun in the middle of New York City—an Art Deco fever dream of how the 1930s imagined the future. This rush of awe is celebrated every March 27 as World Theatre Day.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.RadioCityHall_EN-US6218301556_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.RadioCityHall_EN-US6218301556_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":false},"Headline":"Still burning bright","Title":"Radio City Music Hall in New York City","Copyright":"© Clarence Holmes Photography/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/40.759968,-73.979912/12?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-US&od=2&shading=flat&pp=40.759968,-73.979912;S9;Radio City Music Hall, New York City&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260327_RadioCityHall\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Theatre+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260327_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260327_RadioCityHall"},"Ssd":"20260327","Name":"RadioCityHall","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6218301556","FullDateString":"Mar 27, 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Running along the remote southwest coast of Vancouver Island in Canada, the West Coast Trail is one of the country's most legendary hikes. Located in British Columbia's Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, the trail stretches about 47 miles through rainforest, beaches, and rocky shoreline. It was established in 1907 as a lifesaving route for shipwreck survivors along what sailors once called the 'Graveyard of the Pacific.'","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LoganCreek_EN-US6075548781_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LoganCreek_EN-US6075548781_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A step above the wild","Title":"Logan Creek Suspension Bridge, West Coast Trail, Canada","Copyright":"© Tandem Stock/Adobe Stock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The West Coast Trail typically takes 6 to 8 days to complete, due to mud, ladders, rivers, and harsh coastal weather.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260326_LoganCreek\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=West+Coast+Trail+hike&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260326_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260326_LoganCreek"},"Ssd":"20260326","Name":"LoganCreek","Market":"EN-US","Hash":"6075548781","FullDateString":"Mar 26, 2026"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Image of the day","